<div id="comment_status_64623217" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64623217" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64623217" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64623217" name="comment_link_64623217" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23386545&amp;cid=64623217" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64623217)" >They never wanted us to have R/W capability here.</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64623217" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64623217); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>, Informative)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~mmell">mmell</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~mmell">( 832646 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64623217">		
		on Saturday July 13, 2024 @11:58AM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23386545&amp;cid=64623217">#64623217</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64623217"><p>First came the Compact Disk . . . only, no, that's not really true.  Anybody here ever heard of Digital Audio Tape, or DAT?  80dB dynamic range, and a digital format so <i>zero</i> crosstalk, thd, platter rumble, wow, flutter, . . . but it was RW and CD's (which cost more to adopt than updating existing tape/cassette technology) were initially RO.  CD's didn't appear in an R/W form until DAT was safely and totally dead.
</p><p>Then came the whole HDDTV/Blu-Ray contest.  The only reason there was ever a writable Blu-Ray disk was so that Sony could make sure HDDTV disks didn't become the standard (you know, like VHS did over Betamax).  Once that was done, Sony had to deal with the concept of people pirating their Blu-Ray properties (because a compatible medium to write your rips is always a nice thing).  Now that Sony's embraced the optical disk as a R/W medium and extended the optical disk as a R/W medium and ensured that there's no pesky HDDTV standard to upset their applecart, they'll extinguish it.
</p><p>Not to worry - it's all available streaming on the intarweb.  And, by the way, this is the SUPER-condensed version of this story.  As someone who has been in the industry these past four decades, there's a lot more story to tell.  This'll do for the <i>Reader's Digest</i> version.  Suffice it to say that Sony is the reason we can't have nice things.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64623217">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64623217" class="btn link" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23386545&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64623217" onclick="D2.replyTo(64623217); return false;">Reply to This</a> 	<a rel="nofollow" href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
